Lab 9: From quap() to ulam()

Author

Jesse Brunner

Published

March 8, 2023

Weâre graduating from models where quadratic approximation, using quap(), will suffice to situations where weâll need a general purpose integrator to estimate the posterior. There are a number that might fit the bill, in particular those using Gibbs samplers (e.g., BUGS, JAGS), but weâre going to use a Hamiltonian MCMC method implemented in Stan. Stan is really a computer programming language of sorts and it can involve different sorts of thinking than weâre used to using in R or in specifying our models so far. This is not to say that we canât or shouldnât write models in Stan directlyâindeed, weâll start looking at Stan code very soonâbut McElreath has created an interface with Stan (or perhaps translator) called ulam() that keeps the syntax virtually the same as weâve been using, which is blessedly close to how we might write a model on paper.

Today our goals are to:

  • convince ourselves that ulam() works just like our quap() models so far, including all of the things we do with it.
  • see how to assess whether our model is working well at estimating the posterior, looking at trace plots, etc.
  • peek under the hood to see what the Stan code actually looks like and does.

Back to the weight by height example

Remember the !Kung height and weight data in the Howell1 data set?

library(rethinking)
data("Howell1")
# rename for simplicity
df <- Howell1

head(df)

1 151.765 47.82561  63    1
2 139.700 36.48581  63    0
3 136.525 31.86484  65    0
4 156.845 53.04191  41    1

6 163.830 62.99259  35    1

We may recall that the log of weight increased more-or-less linearly with height, which we centered on the mean height. We also considered how this relationship varied between males and females in the data set. Thus our model was written like this. \[ \begin{align} \log(y_i) & \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_i, \sigma) \\ \mu_i & = \alpha[sex] + \beta[sex] x_i \\ \alpha & \sim \text{Normal}(50,10) \\ \beta & \sim \text{Normal}(0.25, 0.25) \\ \sigma & \sim \text{Exponential}(1) \end{align} \] First, letâs prepare the data

xbar <- mean(df$height)
df$hc <- df$height -  xbar
df$lwt <- log(df$weight)
df$sex <- df$male + 1

head(df)

Fitting our model

`quap()

We can recycle prior code for the quap() version of the model:

# quap version
m_q <- quap(
  alist(
    lwt ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a[sex] + b[sex]*hc,
    a[sex] ~ dnorm(2.5, 0.1), 
    b[sex] ~ dnorm(0.02, 0.005),
    sigma ~ dexp(1)
  ), data=df
)

precis(m_q, depth=2, digits = 3)
            mean           sd       5.5%      94.5%
a[1]  3.46015276 0.0061595109 3.45030867 3.46999685
a[2]  3.42047714 0.0065081181 3.41007591 3.43087837
b[1]  0.02136308 0.0002356789 0.02098642 0.02173974
b[2]  0.01991102 0.0002237522 0.01955342 0.02026862
sigma 0.10346752 0.0031401472 0.09844896 0.10848608

ulam()

Now letâs see what the ulam() version looks like:

# ulam version
m_u <- ulam(
  alist(
    lwt ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a[sex] + b[sex]*hc,
    a[sex] ~ dnorm(2.5, 0.1), 
    b[sex] ~ dnorm(0.02, 0.005),
    sigma ~ dexp(1)
  ), data=df, 
  chains = 4, cores = 4 
)

Itâs the same syntax, except that a) we use ulam() in place of quap() and b) we might want to specify the number of chains to run (and the number of computer cores on which to run those chains). OK, and we get a lot more output (not shown here).

reading through the verbose output of a Stan model

Take a second and scroll through that output. We see:

  1. The model compiles, which takes a second. The model is actually being translated in a way by Stan into C code1 so that it can run efficiently. This compilation takes a bit sometimes, but it pays off dividends in much faster model runs!
  2. We then see the chains starting to run. We get status reports on the iteration number theyâre on every 100 iterations out of the default 1000 iterations.
  3. The first half of the iterations are called Warmup and the last half are Sampling. Warmup is not like in Gibbs sampling where the first (arbitrary) number of samples are thrown away because it takes a while for the chains to find the posterior. Instead the warmup period is all about finding appropriate steps sizes for your posterior and other aspects of tuning the HMC integrator.
  4. Finally we see when the chains are finishing, or if there were some problems youâll get a probably cryptic message about what happened.

You may also see Informational Messageâs about rejected proposals. For instance, I saw one (on one run)

Chain 3 Informational Message: The current Metropolis proposal is about to be rejected because of the following issue:
Chain 3 Exception: normal_lpdf: Scale parameter is 0, but must be positive! (in '/var/folders/lm/75nnf8ws1cn_9j3184tr6bnh0000gn/T/RtmpSe7Jwy/model-9d748b56f5d.stan', line 23, column 4 to column 31)

First note that the line number and column are in the resulting Stan code that ulam() generated. Iâll show you below how to see that code. But for now, lets just see what this message means. In essence, the scale parameter of the normal distribution (âlpdfâ stands for log probability density functionâ¦ that is, itâs normal distribution function is like dnorm(..., log=TRUE)), which is the standard deviation, was on occasionally coming up as zero! The standard deviation should be positive, right? But weâve actually used a prior distribution for it that allows values to be zero. (See what the probability density of getting a zero is from an exponential distribution.) This rarely happens, which is why itâs OK for us to use an exponential distribution for the prior of something that must be positive, even though it does not, technically, keep zeros from popping up here and there.

Anyway, thatâs the messages and such. What does it look like? How does the output compare with that from quap()?

precis(m_q, depth=2, digits=3)
            mean           sd       5.5%      94.5%
a[1]  3.46015276 0.0061595109 3.45030867 3.46999685
a[2]  3.42047714 0.0065081181 3.41007591 3.43087837
b[1]  0.02136308 0.0002356789 0.02098642 0.02173974
b[2]  0.01991102 0.0002237522 0.01955342 0.02026862
sigma 0.10346752 0.0031401472 0.09844896 0.10848608
precis(m_u, depth=2, digits=3)
            mean           sd       5.5%      94.5%     n_eff     Rhat4
a[1]  3.45991343 0.0065967183 3.44918780 3.47075055  959.2695 1.0074133
a[2]  3.42040745 0.0067252940 3.40977000 3.43136055 1063.5939 1.0025214
b[1]  0.02135692 0.0002425380 0.02098204 0.02172831 2099.2253 1.0010869
b[2]  0.01991942 0.0002259657 0.01955765 0.02027571 2304.9143 0.9986876
sigma 0.10402039 0.0032015932 0.09912035 0.10929510  773.5417 1.0027304

They are darn near identical in terms of their parameter estimates and the CIs. We also see two extra columns. The Rhat4 is a measure of convergence. We want to see it basically be equal to 1. If it gets above 1.05 weâve got some convergence issues. (See ?Rhat for more.)

The n_eff column tells us how many essentially independent samples from the posterior we have for each parameter. Remember that we have a chain of samples from the posterior where each sample depends only on the previous sample. If those samples are correlated, they provide less information about the posterior than if they were independent. This uses some fancy logic to estimate the equivalent number of samples (or lenght of our chain) if all of the samples were independent of each other. Notice that we have fewer effective samples for sigma and more for the b parameter. You may also see that we might have more effective samples than actual samples (500 samples/chain \(\times\) 4 chains = 2000)! As McElreath notes in his book, sometimes a good sampler can do much better than random!

Letâs keep up the comparison:

The relationship between parameters, and the way you use the pairs() plot function are virtually identical.

We can also extract samples just the same way:

post_q <- extract.samples(m_q, n=1000)
hist(post_q$sigma, col=NULL)

post_u <- extract.samples(m_u, n=1000)
hist(post_u$sigma, col=NULL, border = "red", add=T)

So those are the same, too.

Checking model convergence

We should generally start our post-fitting routine by checking the HMC modelâs convergence on the posterior before doing inferential things, like plotting posterior predictions! So letâs learn how to do that.

Weâve seen the Rhat statistic in the precis() output, which should give us some confidence in model fit

precis(m_u, depth=2, digits = 3)
            mean           sd       5.5%      94.5%     n_eff     Rhat4
a[1]  3.45991343 0.0065967183 3.44918780 3.47075055  959.2695 1.0074133
a[2]  3.42040745 0.0067252940 3.40977000 3.43136055 1063.5939 1.0025214
b[1]  0.02135692 0.0002425380 0.02098204 0.02172831 2099.2253 1.0010869
b[2]  0.01991942 0.0002259657 0.01955765 0.02027571 2304.9143 0.9986876
sigma 0.10402039 0.0032015932 0.09912035 0.10929510  773.5417 1.0027304

and those were encouraging. We can also use traceplots and âtrankplotsâ to get a sense of whether our chains are mixing in parameter space. That is, are they covering the same values of parameters?

traceplot(m_u)

We can see the trace of our chains through parameter space. The grey is the warmup period, where we start at all sorts of places and then end up converging on the region of parameter space for the sampling period. Our chains look good. (Unfortunately while McElreathâs code says it should be able to remove trim observations from the start, he hasnât actually implemented this, so thereâs no way to get his plots to focus on a narrower range of parameter space.)

Rank plots show something similar, which suggests no chains are consistently higher or lower than the others in parameter space.

trankplot(m_u)

This is all very good!

Peeking under the hood

Lastly, I want to show you that you can see the actual Stan code produced by ulam(). It is worth seeing what this actually looks like.

stancode(m_u)
data{
    array[544] int male;
     vector[544] age;
     vector[544] weight;
     vector[544] height;
     vector[544] lwt;
     vector[544] hc;
    array[544] int sex;
}
parameters{
     vector[2] a;
     vector[2] b;
     real<lower=0> sigma;
}
model{
     vector[544] mu;
    sigma ~ exponential( 1 );
    b ~ normal( 0.02 , 0.005 );
    a ~ normal( 2.5 , 0.1 );
    for ( i in 1:544 ) {
        mu[i] = a[sex[i]] + b[sex[i]] * hc[i];
    }
    lwt ~ normal( mu , sigma );
}
